        consumed tap <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">water</ENAMEX> at home sometimes or always (<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">47/49</NUMEX> [<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">96%</NUMEX>]
        of cases and <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">68/99</ENAMEX> [<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">69%</NUMEX>] of controls), <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">20/47</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">42%</NUMEX>) of cases
        and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">32/68</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">47%</NUMEX>) of controls filtered their <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">water</ENAMEX> sometimes
        or always, and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">5/47</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">11%</NUMEX>) of cases and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">10/68</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">15%%</NUMEX>) of
        controls boiled their <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">water</ENAMEX> sometimes or always.
        In spite of its limitations, our study suggests that the
        relative risk of cryptosporidiosis among <ENAMEX TYPE="DISEASE">AIDS</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">patients</ENAMEX> from
        drinking tap <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">water</ENAMEX> is high (adjusted OR, <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">23.6</NUMEX> for highest
